# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: barcelona
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] The **1888 Barcelona Universal Exposition** (in Catalan: ***Exposició Universal de Barcelona*** and ***Exposición Universal de Barcelona*** in Spanish) was Spain's first International World's Fair and ran from 8 April to 9 December 1888.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] The second one in Barcelona was held in 1929.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] Eugenio Serrano de Casanova (journalist, writer and entrepreneur) tried to launch an exposition in 1886, and when that failed, the Mayor of Barcelona, Francesc Rius i Taulet, took over the planning of the project.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] The fair was hosted on the reconstructed 115-acre (47 ha) site of the city's main public park, the Parc de la Ciutadella, with Vilaseca's Arc de Triomf forming the entrance.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] More than 2 million people from Spain, the rest of Europe, and other international points of embarkation visited the exhibition, which made the equivalent of $1,737,000 USD.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] The fair was opened by Alfonso XIII of Spain and Maria Christina of Austria.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] Twenty-seven countries participated, including China, Japan and the United States.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] The piano manufacturer Erard sponsored a series of 20 concerts featuring Isaac Albéniz, a Catalan pianist and composer best known for his piano works based on folk music idioms.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] The artistic director was Tomàs Moragas.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] Luisa Lacal de Bracho won a gold medal and Josep Maria Tamburini won a silver medal at the exhibition.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] The main legacy of the 1888 World Fair is the Ciutadella Park: the World Fair served as the opportunity for Barcelona to rid itself of the hated citadel and transform it into a central park for the city's denizens.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] Another product of the World Fair is the *Modernista* or *Neo-Mudéjar* Arc de Triomf (triumphal arch), the Fair's former gateway, presiding over Passeig de Lluís Companys.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] The Columbus Monument (*Monument a Colom*), a 60 m (197 ft) tall monument to Christopher Columbus, was built for the exposition on the site where Columbus returned to Europe after his first voyage to the Americas.
[src:barcelona/1888-barcelona-universal-exposition] It was erected at the lower end of *Les Rambles* and remains standing today.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:barcelona/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:barcelona/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The **1904 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the III Olympiad** and also known as **St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Louis 1904**) were an international multi-sport event held in St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, Missouri, United States, from 1 July to 23 November 1904.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Many events were conducted at what is now known as Francis Field on the campus of Washington University in St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] This was the first time that the Olympic Games were held outside Europe.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Tensions caused by the Russo–Japanese War and difficulties in traveling to St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Louis resulted in very few top-class athletes from outside the United States and Canada taking part in the 1904 Games.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Only 69–74 of the 651 athletes who competed came from outside North America, and only between 12 and 15 nations were represented in all.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Some events subsequently combined the U.S. national championship with the Olympic championship.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The current three-medal format of gold, silver and bronze for first, second and third place was introduced at the 1904 Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] After the first two editions of the Olympic Games were awarded to Athens and Paris, the IOC's first open bidding process was held for the 1904 Olympics at the 4th IOC Session in Paris in May 1901.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago civic leaders, including University of Chicago president William Rainey Harper, formed the International Olympian Games Association in February 1901 to plan for hosting the Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Shortly before the session began, another American bid was submitted from St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, which was then preparing to host the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, a World's Fair in 1903.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] At the session, representatives of Chicago offered to put $100,000 (equivalent to $3,870,000 in 2025) toward the games.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Unable to compete with this, all other countries withdrew their bids before the IOC voted; cities which had previously expressed interest in the 1904 games included Berlin, Copenhagen, and Stockholm.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC delegates then voted between the choices of Chicago and St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, with Chicago winning unanimously on May 21.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Louis was forced to postpone its World's Fair from 1903 to 1904, it began planning athletic events that would compete directly with the Olympics in Chicago.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Louis and planned to hold its national championships at the World's Fair.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] In the meantime, Chicago's plans for a new stadium on the shore of Lake Michigan seating 75,000 met considerable opposition from local leaders, including Aaron Montgomery Ward, putting the centerpiece of Chicago's Olympic bid into question.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] On December 23, 1902, fearing that the dispute would permanently damage the Olympic movement, the IOC asked its members to approve, by a postal vote, the transfer of the Olympic Games to St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] When the votes were tallied, IOC founder Pierre de Coubertin telegraphed the Chicago committee on February 10, 1903, to inform them that the Games had been moved.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing, dumbbells, catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling), and the decathlon made their debuts.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The swimming events were held in a temporary pond near Skinker and Wydown Boulevards, where "lifesaving demonstrations" of unsinkable lifeboats for ocean liners took place.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago runner James Lightbody won the steeplechase and the 800 m and then set a natural world record in the 1500 m.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Harry Hillman won both the 200 m and 400 m hurdles and also the flat 400 m.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Sprinter Archie Hahn was champion in the 60 m, 100 m and 200 m.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] In this last race, he set an Olympic record in 21.6, a natural record that stood for 28 years.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] In the discus, after American Martin Sheridan had thrown exactly the same distance as his compatriot, Ralph Rose (39.28 m), the judges gave them both an extra throw to decide the winner.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Sheridan won the decider and claimed the gold medal.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Ray Ewry again won all three standing jumps.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The team representing Great Britain was awarded a total of two medals, both won by Irish athletes.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The top non-U.S. athlete was Emil Rausch of Germany, who won three swimming events.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Zoltán Halmay of Hungary and Charles Daniels of the United States each won two swimming gold medals.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Galt Football Club from Canada won the gold medal in football.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The organizers of the World's Fair held "Anthropology Days" on August 12 and 13.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Since the 1889 Paris Exposition, human zoos, as a key feature of world's fairs, functioned as demonstrations of anthropological notions of race, progress, and civilization.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] These goals were followed also at the 1904 World's Fair.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Fourteen hundred indigenous people from Southeast Asia, the Pacific Islands, East Asia, Africa, the Middle East, South America and North America were displayed in anthropological exhibits that showed them in their natural habitats.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Another 1600 indigenous people displayed their culture in other areas of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition (LPE), including on the fairgrounds and at the Model School, where American Indian boarding schools students demonstrated their successful assimilation.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The sporting event itself took place with the participation of about 100 paid indigenous men.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Contests included "baseball throwing, shot put, running, broad jumping, weight lifting, pole climbing, and tugs-of-war before a crowd of approximately ten thousand".
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] No women participated in Anthropology Days, though some, notably the Fort Shaw Indian School girls basketball team, did compete in other athletic events at the LPE.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] According to theorist Susan Brownell, world's fairs – with their inclusion of human zoos – and the Olympics were a logical fit at this time, as they "were both linked to an underlying cultural logic that gave them a natural affinity".
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Also, one of the original intentions of Anthropology Days was to create publicity for the official Olympic events.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The 1904 Summer Olympic program featured 16 sports encompassing 95 events in 18 disciplines.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] In July 2021 the IOC accepted the recommendation of Olympic historian Bill Mallon regarding which sports and events should be considered as Olympic.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing made its Olympic debut at the St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The sport has since featured at every Summer Olympics, except for the 1912 Stockholm Games.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] While wrestling made a return, it was exclusively the newly debuted catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling) as opposed to Greco-Roman style of the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Five nations were represented, with each of the 42 competitors having resided in the United States.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Later editions would have both styles of wrestling in their programs.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Basketball, hurling, American football and Gaelic football were featured as unofficial sports.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] There was a demonstration bout of women's boxing.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Baseball is also noted by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to have appeared at the Games, though it does not appear in the list compiled by Olympic historian Bill Mallon and any results are not known.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake is located further west.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Five sports venues were used for the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The venues included Glen Echo Country Club, the first golf course constructed west of the Mississippi River, which had opened in 1901.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Three Olympic sports were hosted at Forest Park, the site of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition which was being held concurrently with the Olympics: the Life Saving Exhibition Lake at Forest Park was used for the diving, swimming, and water polo events.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake became the first park of St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The Lake has hosted rowing regattas since 1882 and still hosts them as of 2010.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Francis Olympic Field and Gymnasium are still in use on the Washington University in St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] An ornamental gate commemorating the 1904 Games was constructed outside the stadium immediately after the Exposition.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] A swimming pool was added to the gymnasium in 1985.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Forest Park, constructed in 1876, is still in use as of 2021 and attracts over 12 million visitors annually.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Glen Echo Country Club remains in use as a golf course today as of 2021.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Athletes from thirteen nations competed in St.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of known competitors for each nation.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] Louis in 1904, and European tensions caused by the Russo-Japanese War, only 69–74 athletes from outside North America participated in the Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] These are the nations that won medals at the 1904 Games.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The nationalities of some medalists were disputed, as many American athletes were recent immigrants to the United States who had not yet been granted U.S. citizenship.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] These cases saw medals credited to the United States transferred to other countries or mixed teams.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] In addition, the IOC had counted one gold, one silver, and two bronze medals won by the American fencer Albertson Van Zo Post for Cuba instead of the United States.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC also had shown Charles Tatham as a Cuban medal-winner for individual fencing events (foil and épée) and American silver medalist in the team foil event, but he was an American.
[src:barcelona/1904-summer-olympics] All are now credited to the United States.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The **1908 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the IV Olympiad** and also known as **London 1908**) were an international multi-sport event held in London, England, from 27 April to 31 October 1908.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games were relocated to London after Italy withdrew from hosting on financial grounds.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Archival research has established that the British Olympic Association was already privately exploring the possibility of London hosting the Games as early as 5 January 1906, three months before the eruption began.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] London was formally confirmed as host on 19 November 1906.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Rome eventually hosted the Games in 1960.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] These were the fourth chronological modern Summer Olympics in keeping with the now-accepted four-year cycle as opposed to the alternate four-year cycle of the proposed Intercalated Games.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The IOC president for these Games was Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Lasting a total of 187 days (six months and four days), these were the longest Games in modern Olympics history.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] There were four bids for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Rome was selected ahead of London, Berlin and Milan.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The selection was made at the 6th IOC Session in London in 1904.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Italian authorities were preparing to stage the games when Mount Vesuvius erupted on 7 April 1906, devastating the city of Naples.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Funds were diverted to the reconstruction of Naples, so a new host country was required.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] During the Intercalated Games of Athens, still in April 1906, Coubertin approached Lord Desborough about alternatively hosting in London.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Accepting the offer and with a mere 18 months in which to prepare, London was selected for the first time to hold the Games, which were held at White City alongside the Franco-British Exhibition, at the time the more noteworthy event.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The White City Stadium, built in short time for the Games, held 68,000 people, with full crowds turning up to watch the events.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The stadium track was three laps to the mile (536.448 metres per lap), as the current standard of 400 metres did not exist until 1962, with a pool (for swimming and diving events) and platforms (for wrestling and gymnastics) in the centre field.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] On the opening day, following the practice introduced at the Intercalated Games of 1906, teams paraded behind national flags.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Olympics also prompted establishment of standard rules for sports, and selection of judges from different countries rather than just the host.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] One reason was the 400 metre race, in which a US runner, John Carpenter, was accused by the British officials of interfering with a British runner.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Part of the problem was the different definition of interference under British and international rules (the events were held under British rules by the decision of the Organising Committee).
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The officials decided to disqualify Carpenter and ordered a second final race without him.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] British Halswelle was to face the other two finalists.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] These athletes, William Robbins and John Taylor, were both Americans and decided not to participate in the repeat of the final to protest against the judges' decision.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Halswelle was thus the only medallist in the 400 metres.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The most famous incident of the games came at the end of the marathon.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Dorando Pietri, Italy, began his race at a rather slow pace, but in the second half of the course began a powerful surge moving him into second position by the 32 km (20 mi) mark, 4 minutes behind South African Charles Hefferon.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] When he knew that Hefferon was in crisis, Pietri further increased his pace, overtaking him at the 39 km (24 mi) mark.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The effort took its toll and with only two kilometres to go, Pietri began to feel the effects of extreme fatigue and dehydration.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] When he entered the stadium, he took the wrong path and when umpires redirected him, he fell down for the first time.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] He got up with their help, in front of 75,000 spectators.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] He fell four more times, and each time the umpires helped him up.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] In the end, though totally exhausted, he managed to finish the race in first place.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Of his total time of 2h 54min 46s, ten minutes were needed for that last 340 metres.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The American team immediately lodged a complaint against the help Pietri received from the umpires.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The complaint was accepted and Pietri was disqualified and removed from the final standings of the race.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Since he had not been responsible for his disqualification, Queen Alexandra awarded him a gilded silver cup the next day.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to include winter events, as had originally been proposed for the Games.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] There were four figure skating events, although held on 28 and 29 October, months after most of the other events.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Oscar Swahn from Sweden, who won the gold medal for running deer shooting, became the oldest Olympic champion of all time, and set another age record by being 72 years and 279 days old during his triumph at the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] One of the more unusual shooting events in 1908 was Olympic dueling.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The discipline, which was an associate event (that is, not official), was performed by facing opponents wearing protective clothing and masks and firing wax bullets.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] American John Taylor was a member of the winning medley relay team, making him the first African-American athlete to win an Olympic gold medal.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Times for the winning team were United States (3:29.4): William Hamilton, 200 metres (22.0); Nathaniel Cartmell, 200 metres (22.2); John Taylor, 400 metres (49.8); and Melvin Sheppard, 800 metres (1:55.4).
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Less than five months after returning from the Olympic Games in London, Taylor died of typhoid fever on 2 December 1908 at the age of 26.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The budget of the organising committee showed a cost of £15,000; over one-third was labelled "entertainment expense".
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Donations were the major source of revenue; only 28% of income derived from ticket sales.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Total receipts of £21,378 resulted in organisers claiming a profit.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Construction of the White City Stadium, which cost the government about £60,000, was not counted.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Twenty-two sports, representing 110 events in 25 sporting disciplines, were competed.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] A golf tournament had also been planned but it was cancelled a few days before it was scheduled to start.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving, and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] At the time, tug-of-war was part of athletics and the two different football codes (association and rugby (union)) were listed together.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee now considers tug-of-war a separate sport as well as referring to association football as simply "football" and to rugby union as "rugby." In one of seven cycling events (cycling sprint) no medals were awarded.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The sailing program was open for a total of five sailing classes, but actually only four sailing events were competed.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Cycle polo, glima and pistol dueling were demonstration sports.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Thirteen sports venues were used for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The first winter sports took place at Prince's Skating Club in Knightsbridge.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] White City Stadium served as a precursor to modern stadiums.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The figure skating events were not held at the next Olympics in Stockholm, but returned for the 1920 Games in Antwerp, heralding the first Winter Olympics that took place in Chamonix in 1924.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] White City was the main venue for the 1934 British Empire Games (known as the Commonwealth Games since 1978) and, before its demolition in 1985, also served as a venue for the 1966 FIFA World Cup.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The All England Lawn Tennis Club continues to host the Wimbledon championships and is the only venue of the 1908 Games that was used for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Bisley and Henley served as venues in the 1948 Games when the Olympics returned to London forty years later.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games featured athletes representing 22 National Olympic Committees.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Finland, Turkey and New Zealand (as part of the team from Australasia) made their first appearance at the Olympic Games.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] The fact that the United Kingdom competed as a single team was upsetting to some Irish competitors, who felt that Ireland should compete on its own, despite being part of the UK at the time.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] They relied on the precedent set by Grand Duchy of Finland, which while being a part of the Russian Empire, competed in London as a separate country.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Fearing an Irish boycott, the authorities changed the name of the team to Great Britain/Ireland, and in two sports, field hockey and polo, Ireland participated as a separate country, winning silver medals in both, although their medals counted towards the UK's tally.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Irish athletes in the United States were not affected by this controversy, and many Irish immigrants to the United States competed for the U.S.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team as members of the Irish American Athletic Club.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Members of the Irish American Athletic Club won ten of the U.S.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team's total 23 gold medals, or as many as the nations of France, Germany and Italy combined.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] Britain had more than a quarter of competitors in their team, with 676, compared to 112 on the American team which placed second in the medal standings.
[src:barcelona/1908-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1908 Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The **1912 Summer Olympics** (Swedish: *Olympiska sommarspelen 1912*), officially known as the **Games of the V Olympiad** (Swedish: *Den V olympiadens spel*) and commonly known as **Stockholm 1912**, were an international multi-sport event held in Stockholm, Sweden, between 6 July and 22 July 1912.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held on 6 July.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] They were the only Summer Olympics to be held in the 1910s as the 1916 Summer Olympics in Berlin were cancelled due to World War I.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Twenty-eight nations and 2,408 competitors, including 48 women, competed in 102 events in 14 sports.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] With the exception of tennis (starting on 5 May) and football and shooting (both starting on 29 June), the games were held within a month with an official opening on 6 July.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] It was the last Olympics to issue solid gold medals and, with Japan's debut, the first time an official team from an Asian nation participated.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Stockholm was the only bid for the games, and was selected in 1909.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The games were the first to have art competitions, women's diving, women's swimming, and the first to feature both the decathlon and the new pentathlon, both won by the American Jim Thorpe.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Electric timing was introduced in athletics, while the host country disallowed boxing.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Figure skating was rejected by the organizers because they wanted to promote the Nordic Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (26), while hosts Sweden won the most medals overall (65).
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games for eight years due to the disruption of the First World War.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The next Olympic Games were held in 1920 in Antwerp.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Following the 1908 Summer Olympics in London, authorities in Sweden immediately sought to ensure that the next games would be held there.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] There were two Swedish members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) at the time, Viktor Balck and Clarence von Rosen.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The pair proposed the idea to the Swedish governing bodies of athletics and gymnastics in order to ensure that they backed any potential bid.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Support was given by the national associations on 18 April 1909 for a bid to host the Olympics in Stockholm on the basis that suitable financial arrangements could be made.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] King Gustaf V was petitioned on 6 May 1909 following the publication of preliminary plans for the Stockholm bid that the expected cost of hosting the Games would be 415,000 kronor (£23,050 or $115,250).
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Government accepted the petition on behalf of the King and supported the bid.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] On 28 May, at the meeting of the IOC in Berlin, the Swedish representatives declared that they had full financial support for hosting the next Games in Stockholm.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] A deal was made with the German IOC representative on the basis that Berlin would host the 1916 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin spoke at the meeting about his concerns that Sweden should ensure that the Games take place, as he did not want a repeat of the problems with Great Britain hosting the 1908 Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The news that Stockholm was to host the 1912 Olympics was received with enthusiasm by the Swedish public.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The organizing committee took de Coubertin's words to heart, and aimed to achieve an Olympic Games which removed those elements which detracted from earlier Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The committee was elected in the autumn of 1909, with Balck voted as the President of the committee, and Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf selected as Honorary President.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The committee's first meeting took place on 7 October, and on 11 October they delegated the arrangements for the individual branches of sports to the relevant governing bodies in Sweden.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] There were four exceptions to this, with the game shooting, modern pentathlon and mountain ascents retained by the Olympic committee, and the horse riding competitions being organized by Prince Carl, Duke of Västergötland, who was the inspector of the Swedish cavalry.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Altogether there were 187 members of these committees.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The official invitation to compete in the Games was issued on 18 November 1910 to 27 countries, either directly or through their representative on the IOC.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] A further 15 countries were to have been invited, but as they had no IOC representatives, the Swedish authorities were unsure how to proceed.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Once the organizing committee for the Games received confirmation of the athletic associations in each of the 15 countries, they too were sent invitations.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Some 61,800 entry forms were printed for the use of the various nations.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Free transport was arranged for the invited nations' equipment, and a discount of 50 percent was arranged for competitors and delegates on the state run railway.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] A daily newspaper which only covered the Olympics was arranged to be published during the Games, in both English and Swedish.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Further arrangements were made for the general arrival of visitors in order to entertain them whilst they were not at the Games; a pleasure garden was opened north of the Olympic Stadium, and a series of indoor tennis courts were converted into a restaurant.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Twelve sports venues were used in the 1912 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that more than one venue would be used for the football tournament, which has been the case ever since.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Stockholm Olympic Stadium served as one of the equestrian venues for the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Råsunda Stadium served as a venue for the 1958 FIFA World Cup and the 1995 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In the initial bid document it was identified that a new stadium would be needed, initially envisaged as being located in the Östermalm Athletic Grounds.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In order to save funds, it was expected that only one of the stadium's stands would be permanent, with the other three made of wood and dismantled following the Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The cost of that stadium was estimated at 235,000 Kronor.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Arrangements were made with the individual national committees to provide the use of Östermalm Athletic Grounds and Traneberg.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The cycling road race was held around Mälaren, the third largest lake in Sweden.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The water events, including the swimming and the rowing, were held at Djurgårdsbrunnsviken, where a stadium was built.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Kaknäs was already used as a shooting range, but alterations were needed to accommodate shooting events.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Although it was not used as the Olympic stadium as originally intended, Östermalm hosted the lawn tennis and fencing competitions after a tennis pavilion was moved there from another location.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Five other locations were considered in addition to the Östermalm Athletic Grounds to locate the Olympic Stadium.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Stockholm Olympic Stadium was built on the site of the former Stockholm Athletic Grounds in order to retain the other locations for other uses during the Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] By placing it to the north of the city, the Olympic Stadium was within the immediate vicinity of other pre-existing sporting venues.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Initial funding was given to the sum of 400,000 Kr for a timber stadium but Torben Grut, the architect, also drew up alternative plans for a stone stadium.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] However it was found that the original estimate for the stone stadium would still be too expensive, and the plans were once more modified in order to simplify the design and reduce costs.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] An agreement was entered into with a contractor on 2 November 1910 that it would be transferred complete by 25 May 1912.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Games of the V Olympiad were opened on 6 July 1912.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish Royal Family left Stockholm Palace at 10:40am, and were received at the Olympic Stadium by members of the IOC.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Three thousand competing athletes had already assembled in the nearby Östermalm Athletic Grounds, and began to enter the stadium in alphabetical order by nation according to the Swedish spelling.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish team entered last, but unlike the later tradition, the Greek team did not enter first.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] A hymn was sung, a traditional Swedish chant was conducted and prayers were read first in Swedish and then in English.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf addressed the King on behalf of the Swedish Olympic Association.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Afterwards a trumpet fanfare was played and the Crown Prince called for cheers for the King.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The athletes in their national groups marching out of the stadium in order ended the ceremony.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish delegation at the IOC meeting in Berlin on 28 May 1909 had proposed a simple Olympic schedule containing only "pure" athletics, swimming, gymnastics and wrestling.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] However other countries requested that the schedule be more comprehensive, and with that in mind they put forward a further programme at the IOC meeting in 1911 which was met with approval.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The sports which were added were the tug of war, cycling, fencing, football, horse riding, lawn tennis, rowing, shooting, skating and yacht racing.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The question of adding skating to the programme was discussed once more on 7 February 1910, with the decision being made to drop it from the schedule.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] It was felt to be unsuitable because it was a winter sport, and it was to be part of the Nordic Games the following year.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Boxing was removed from the programme as it was unappealing to the Swedes.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Art competitions were considered at a further meeting on 14 February 1910, and were subsequently added to the programme, but now art competitions are no longer regarded as official Olympic events by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] As a result, now the 1912 Summer Olympics programme considered composed of 14 sports encompassing 18 disciplines and 102 events.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Baseball, Glima (as the second Olympic demonstration of the sport after 1908 Summer Olympics) and Gotland sports were unofficial demonstration sports.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] This was also the first year art competitions were held at the Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The athletic events saw the introduction of a fully automatic timing system developed by R.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] It involved attaching electromagnets to chronometers in a system which attached a control lamp to the starting gun for each race.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] This resulted in the firing of the gun starting a timer which was then stopped by one of the judges at the finishing line.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The final of the men's 100 metres was expected to be a mostly American affair, and it ended up with six athletes, only one of whom was not from the United States.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] It suffered from seven false starts before the athletes finally got away, with Ralph Craig winning the gold medal by 60 centimetres (24 in) in front of second place Alvah Meyer.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Donald Lippincott won bronze, 15 cm behind the second man.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Shizo Kanakuri, a Japanese marathon runner, went missing during the race.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] He lost consciousness by heatstroke and a farming family helped him to stop at a party taking place in a villa on the marathon route in order to quench his thirst, then caught a train to Stockholm and left the country the next day.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] He returned to Japan without notifying race officials.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Fifty years later, after being invited back by the Swedish authorities, he completed the race with an (unofficial) time of 54 years, 8 months, 6 days, 8 hours, 32 minutes and 20.3 seconds.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Portuguese Francisco Lázaro died from heat exhaustion while running the marathon, the only athlete to die during the running of an Olympic marathon.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In addition to the physical toll of the event, the reported split time for the 5 km checkpoint at Stocksund (2:17:20 after a 1:48:00 start) implies an unusually slow 29:20 opening segment, followed by an unrealistically fast 10 km pace.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Martin has noted this discrepancy as a likely timing error.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] American Jim Thorpe won the pentathlon and the newly created decathlon.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Thorpe's gold medals were stripped by the International Olympic Committee in 1913, after the IOC learned that Thorpe had taken expense money for playing baseball, violating contemporary Olympic amateurism rules, before the 1912 Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] This moved everyone else up in the rankings.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In 1982, the IOC was convinced that the disqualification had been improper, as no protest against Thorpe's eligibility had been brought within the required 30 days, and reinstated Thorpe's medals.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The replicas were presented to his children in 1983, 30 years after Thorpe's death.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Finally, in 2022, the IOC posthumously declared Thorpe as the sole winner of the pentathlon and decathlon events after extensive consultations with his former competitors' families who said they had always viewed Thorpe as the winner.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] New Olympic records were set in the majority of track and field events, with only the men's 200 metres, 10 km walk, standing high jump, standing broad jump, hop, step and jump, and the hurdle competitions failing to have new records set.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Tell Berna captured a gold for the 3000m and Henry S.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] "Harry" Babcock took gold for the pole vault, setting an Olympic Record at 3.95m.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Hannes Kolehmainen was the most successful in setting records at the games, with new Olympic Records set in the 5,000, 10,000 metre and cross country races.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The cycling events at the 1912 Games were limited to a road race around Lake Mälaren, which had already been a successful route for a yearly cycling race.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Although not originally in the schedule, several countries requested that track cycling be added; however, the organizing committee stuck by their plans not to build a new track cycling stadium as the only one in Stockholm had been destroyed in order for the Olympic Stadium to be built.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, Germany had specifically requested Cycle-Polo and Figure-Cycling to be added to the programme, both of which requests were turned down by the committee.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] It was decided to hold the road race as a time trial, and to outlaw any non-competitive cyclists acting as pacemakers.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations entered 151 athletes into the competition, which was a greater number than expected by the committee.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The largest group was from Great Britain, who had entered twelve competitors from England, another twelve from Scotland, and a further nine from Ireland.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The race began on 7 July, with the athletes leaving in groups.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The first group left at 2am, with the remaining groups leaving at intervals of two minutes.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The distance raced was 318 kilometres (198 mi), with South African Rudolph Lewis winning the gold medal in the individual race.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Frederick Grubb of Great Britain won the silver medal, and Carl Schutte of the United States won the bronze.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] However, the average positions of the Swedish team were better than their competitors', and so the Swedish team won the gold medal for the team competition.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The silver and bronze medals followed the individual victories, going to Great Britain and the United States respectively – giving Grubb and Schutte a second medal each of the same varieties.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] All of the medals in the men's competitions were split between the diving teams of the Sweden and Germany.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The men's high dive was a Swedish white out, with Swedish divers taking all three medal positions.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Erik Adlerz took the gold medal, and proceeded to take the gold medal for Sweden in the 10 metre platform too.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Albert Zürner took the silver for Germany, and Gustaf Blomgren won the bronze medal for Sweden.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Another white out occurred in the 3 metre springboard with all three medals going to the German team, with Paul Günther taking gold, Hans Luber in the silver medal position and Kurt Behrens in bronze.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] A 10-metre platform event also took place for women, with Sweden taking two more medals, Greta Johansson in gold and Lisa Regnell in silver.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain's Isabelle White won the bronze medal.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The remaining finalists were all from Sweden.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Equestrian made its first appearance at a modern Olympics in the 1912 Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Although competitions involving horse riding had been included in the programme of 1900, this was the first appearance of modern Olympic staples such as dressage, eventing and show jumping.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] It was expected that the competitors would be military personnel as they would have had the cavalry experience to compete.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was split between the military competitions, prize riding and prize jumping.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In the military competition, seven countries put forward competitors for the individual and team eventing.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Each nation put forward four athletes with the exception of Denmark, which only put forward three.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Some of the countries also nominated reserves in addition to their main athletes.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The total length of the course was 55 kilometres (34 mi) with the start and finish both in the grounds of the Field Riding Club.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The heat was such on the day of the event that competitors lost as much as 4.5 pounds (2.0 kg) in weight.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Swede Axel Nordlander won the individual competition, and led the Swedish eventing team to victory as well, earning himself two gold medals.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In second place in the individual competition was German Friedrich von Rochow, who also earned a second silver medal as the team from Germany placed second overall.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Only the bronze medals were split up between nationalities, with the American team including Guy Vernor Henry, Jr. taking the bronze for the team event, while Frenchman Jacques Cariou won the individual medal.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Two additional countries entered for the dressage, although only Sweden entered the maximum number of competitors.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The event resulted in Sweden taking all three medals, with the gold going to Carl Bonde, the silver to Gustaf Adolf Boltenstern and the bronze to Hans von Blixen-Finecke.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The team event saw Sweden take another gold medal, with the French team second and the German team, featuring Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia, in the bronze medal position.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The foil competition became a full Olympic event, having appeared at the 1908 Games as a demonstration sport.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Nedo Nadi and Pietro Speciale of Italy took the gold and silver medals respectively, and Richard Verderber of Austria placed third.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] There were individual and team events in both épée and sabre.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The épée team event saw Belgium take the gold medal and Great Britain and the Netherlands in second and third place respectively.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] A member of the Belgian team went on to take the individual title as well, with Paul Anspach taking the gold medal.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Ivan Joseph Martin Osiier of Denmark took the silver medal, and another Belgian who was not in the team event, Philippe le Hardy de Beaulieu, won the bronze medal.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The sabre competition was dominated by the competitors from Hungary, with their team taking the gold medal over Austria and the Netherlands.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The individual competition saw a shut out by Hungarian athletes with Jenő Fuchs winning the overall competition, Béla Békessy in second and Ervin Mészáros in third.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Thirteen countries signalled their intention to enter football teams for the 1912 Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] A standard cup tie system was implemented, with the final deciding the gold and silver medallists and a third/fourth position playoff deciding the bronze medal winner.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Only FIFA affiliated teams were allowed to take part, with the public draw for the tournament taking place on 18 June 1911.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The tournament itself started on 29 June.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In the first round Finland defeated Italy 3–2, Austria beat Germany 5–1 and the Netherlands emerged victorious over Sweden 4–3.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The team from Great Britain, who had won the gold medal at the 1908 Summer Games, were given a bye to the second round, where they faced Hungary and won 7–0.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Finland also won their match, defeating Russia 2–1.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Denmark matched the British scoreline, winning 7–0 against Norway, and the Netherlands won against Austria 3–1.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The semi final matches pitted Great Britain against Finland, where they won 4–0, and Denmark against the Netherlands, ending in a 4–1 victory for Denmark.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Netherlands won the third/fourth place playoff by the biggest scoreline of the tournament, beating Finland 9–0.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Later on the same day the final was played in the Olympic Stadium, where Great Britain retained its gold medal against Denmark in front of 25,000 spectators.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Goals from Harold Walden, Arthur Berry and two from Gordon Hoare helped Britain to win by a margin of 4–2.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The gymnastic competition at the 1912 Games featured a single individual competition and three team events in addition to a variety of displays by the various teams.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish team naturally won the Gymnastics event of the Swedish system, referred to in the programme as "Team Competition I", with fellow Scandinavian teams Denmark and Norway taking the second and third positions.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The all around team competition came second, with Italy taking the gold.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, one of the Italian team members, Alberto Braglia, won the individual gold for the same event.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Louis Ségura of the French team won the individual silver, while another member of the Italian team, Adolfo Tunesi, won the individual bronze.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The all around team competition saw Hungary take the silver medal and the team from Great Britain in third place.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The final team competition allowed for a free choice of movements and apparatus.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] This was another all Scandinavian affair, with the Norwegian team emerging victorious, Finland in second and Denmark in the bronze medal position.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Modern pentathlon was competed for at the 1912 Games, marking its first appearance in the Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] It was for these games that the five events of shooting, swimming, equestrian, fencing and cross country running were decided to make up the pentathlon.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was spread out across five days from 7 through to 12 July, ending with the cross country race.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Only men participated in the event, although a woman named Helen Preece was briefly enrolled to compete until the organizing committee ultimately denied her entry.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] For the shooting element, each competitor was allowed to bring their own pistol.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The shooting part of the competition was won by Gösta Åsbrink, with Georg de Laval and Gösta Lilliehöök in second and third place respectively, all three representing Sweden.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The swimming event was three lengths, each of 100 metres (330 ft), with the athletes split into eight heats and times going forward to calculate positions.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Ralph Clilverd of Great Britain won this event, with Edmond Bernhardt of Austria in second and de Laval in third.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The fencing competition saw each competitor face off against each other.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Several opponents were noted for their particular skill in the event with Åke Grönhagen of Sweden coming first with 24 wins, Jean de Mas Latrie of France second with 23, Sidney Stranne of Sweden in third with 21 and Patton of the United States close behind with 20.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Thirteen of the competitors cleared the equestrian course without any penalties, with Grönhagen winning the event, Bror Mannström of Sweden in second and de Laval third.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The cross country run was over 4,000 metres and started in the Olympic Stadium itself.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The event was run as a time trial with competitors leaving one minute apart.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] As this was the final event, the winning competitors were announced after the race, with Lilliehöök winning the gold medal, Åsbrink taking silver and de Laval, bronze.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The highest placed non-Swedish competitor was Patton, who finished fifth.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The rowing events at the 1912 Olympics did not prove popular with the public.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] This was put down to the "fatigue" of the public due to the volume of sporting events.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The eight competition was split into heats, with two teams in each heat.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The two British crews were lucky not to be drawn against each other, with the team from Leander Club facing New College, Oxford in the final.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Leander won by a length with a time of 6:15.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The coxed four followed a similar format to the eights, with the German team from Ludwigshafener Ruderverein defeating Britain's Thames Rowing Club in the final.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The competition for the coxed four, inriggers was much smaller, with only four nations competing.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Danish team defeated Sweden in the final.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The single sculls heats proved controversial with the first round race between Mart Kuusik and Alfred Heinrich being re-run after a protest by Heinrich.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, Cecil McVilly was disqualified in the first round after colliding with the boat of Martin Stahnke.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Wally Kinnear of Great Britain defeated Polydore Veirman of Belgium in the final, with Kinnear winning the matchup easily.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The yachts for the sailing competition assembled at Nynäshamn on 19 July, along with the other vessels that were to take part in an Olympic regatta.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The racing itself started the following day with the 12 metre class.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] There were only three nations and yachts competing in this event, the hosts Sweden, as well as Norway and Finland.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Norway won the gold medal, Sweden the silver and Finland came in last place, winning bronze.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The 10 metre class had the same number of countries entering it, although this time Sweden entered two yachts and Russia competed instead of Norway.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish yacht *Kitty* was the winning vessel, with the Finnish boat in second and the Russians coming third.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] A slightly improved field was featured in the 8 metre class, with four countries entering two yachts each.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The medals were awarded to exactly the same nations as the 12 metre class, another all Scandinavian affair.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The 6 metre class saw the most diverse field of any of the sailing events at the 1912 Olympics: six countries entered a total of nine yachts.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] France and Denmark competed in their only sailing event, along with Sweden, sending two yachts each.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Those three nations were the successful in the event, with the French yacht *Mac Miche* taking the gold, the Danish *Nurdug II* taking silver and the Swedish *Kerstin* placing third.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] There were eighteen shooting events at the 1912 Olympics, of which eight were team events.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was split predominantly into three sections: military rifle shooting, shooting with miniature rifles, pistols and revolvers, and clay bird and running deer shooting.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish and American competitors were the most successful at the competition, with seven gold medals each, although Sweden won a total of seventeen medals while the United States team won fourteen.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] 64-year-old Oscar Swahn, part of the Swedish single shot running deer team, is still the oldest gold medal winner in Olympic history.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In swimming, Hawaiian Duke Kahanamoku won the 100 metre freestyle for the United States, who also saw Harry Hebner win gold in the 100 metre backstroke.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Canadian team also took two gold medals, both by George Hodgson in the 400 and 1,500 metre events.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The German swimming team won all three medals in the 200 metre breaststroke, with the gold going to Walter Bathe, who won a further gold in the 400 metre breaststroke.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Australasian team was victorious in the men's relay, with the United States finishing in the silver medal position and Great Britain placing third.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The 1912 Games saw the implementation of swimming events for women, with the 100 metre freestyle and 400 metre team relay taking place.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Fanny Durack won the individual contest, breaking the world record for the distance in the fourth heat.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Her fellow Australian Mina Wylie won the silver medal, and Jennie Fletcher of Great Britain came third to take the bronze medal.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The British team had further success in the women's relay, winning the team relay with the German team in second place and the Austrian team in third.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Because only four countries entered the relay there were no heats; only a final was held.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The United States did not field a women's team.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] New Olympic Records were set in all swimming events at the 1912 Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Tennis on covered courts was agreed initially for the 1912 Games, with competitions run for gentlemen's singles and doubles, ladies' singles, and mixed doubles.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The outdoor tournament was confirmed once the Östermalm Athletic Grounds were completed in late 1911, with the plans modified to have both indoor and outdoor tournaments.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Six countries sent players for the covered court competitions, with representatives from Sweden, Great Britain, Denmark, France, Australasia, and Bohemia appearing.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Included in this lineup was Australasia's only competitor, Anthony Wilding from New Zealand, who was also the reigning Wimbledon gentlemen's champion.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The indoor knockout competition started on 5 May, and continued as expected until the semi-final round where Wilding was beaten by Britain's Charles P.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The British player met Frenchman André Gobert in the final, but Gobert was victorious over the Englishman in straight sets.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Wilding took the bronze medal in a playoff against another British player, Arthur Lowe.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The outdoors tennis competition saw 70 players enter from 12 nations.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] However, Great Britain did not enter any competitors as the dates of the outdoor competition clashed with the 1912 Wimbledon Championships, despite attempts by the British authorities to convince the Olympic organizing committee to change the dates.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Other noted tennis players refused to compete at the Olympics and instead attended Wimbledon.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The gold and silver medals in the gentlemen's singles ended up being decided between two South Africans, with Charles Winslow and Harold Kitson playing each other.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The duo also competed as a pair in the gentlemen's doubles and took the gold medal, beating the Austrians Felix Pipes and Arthur Zborzil.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Marguerite Broquedis of France defeated Dorothea Koring of Germany in the ladies' singles for the gold medal.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In the mixed doubles Koring teamed up with Heinrich Schomburgk to win the gold, the duo defeating Sigrid Fick and Gunnar Setterwall of Sweden in the final.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The tug of war competition was scheduled to take place between 7 and 12 July, with two matches taking place each day.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] However, out of the five countries which elected to enter the competition, only two actually appeared.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain arrived for its match against Bohemia, but the opposition team was nowhere to be found.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The same thing happened once more for the second match, with the Swedish team, made up of policemen from Stockholm, arriving to find that the Austrian team had not arrived.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden was announced as the winners of the match in the Austrians' absence.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] On the second day of the competition, Great Britain took on Sweden, the only occasion where both teams actually turned up for the bout.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The British team were made up of the winners of the gold medal in the same event at the 1908 Games, with the exception of John Sewell and Mathias Hynes.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] As the British team also consisted of policemen, the bout ended up effectively being between the City of London Police and the Stockholm Police, with the Swedish team winning 2–0.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Due to the non-appearance of the team from Luxembourg, that one match ended up being the entire tug of war event at the 1912 Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden was awarded the gold medal and Great Britain the silver.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The water polo tournament was set up on a modified elimination system as there were six teams entered.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The first round saw the British team defeating the Belgian team, Sweden defeating the French team and Austria defeating Hungary.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Lots were drawn to determine which match would take place in the second round as there were three teams left in the competition.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain were drawn to face Sweden, who they defeated.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Austria automatically qualified for the final against the winner of the Britain-Sweden matchup.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain won the gold medal in the event, defeating Austria 8–0.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Playoff matches were then played between each pair of defeated teams in order to decide the second and third places.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden and Belgium played off after a further three matches to decide the silver and bronze medal positions, with Sweden emerging victorious 4–2.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The nations at the 1912 Games entered a total of 267 wrestlers, although the actual competitors who appeared in Sweden were fewer, with 171 actually turning up to compete.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Greco-Roman wrestling was the only style of wrestling competed for at the Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The bouts took place in the open air in an area of the Olympic stadium, with the wrestlers split according to weight into five divisions: featherweight, lightweight, middleweight A (later referred to as middleweight), middleweight B (later referred to as light heavyweight) and heavyweight.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The skills of the competitors from Finland were noted in the featherweight competition, with Kaarlo Koskelo taking the gold medal, while German Georg Gerstäcker took silver and a further medal went to Finland with Otto Lasanen taking bronze.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The lightweight class drew the most attention from the public, with Emil Väre winning gold after beating all of his opponents by pin rather than by points.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Swedish wrestlers Gustaf Malmström and Edvin Mattiasson took the silver and bronze medals respectively.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Claes Johanson won Sweden's only gold medal in the middleweight competition, with his fellow finalist from Russia, Martin Klein, retiring before fighting Johanson in the final.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] This was due to the semi-final match between Klein and Alfred Asikainen of Finland lasting 11 hours and forty minutes, although they took breaks for refreshments every half-hour.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Klein was awarded the silver medal and Asikainen the bronze.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The light heavyweight competition saw another marathon length match, with the bout between Anders Ahlgren of Sweden and Ivar Böhling of Finland for the gold medal lasting more than nine hours.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The match was then declared a draw with both athletes being awarded the silver medal as neither won the match.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The bronze medal went to Hungary's Béla Varga, who was defeated by Ahlgren in the semi-final match.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Yrjö Saarela of Finland was victorious in the heavyweight competition after having placed second in the light heavyweight event at the 1908 Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Johan Olin took another medal for Finland with the silver and Søren Marinus Jensen repeated his bronze medal at the 1908 Olympics with another for Denmark.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The 1912 Summer Olympics saw the introduction of art competitions at the Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Events were implemented for literature, sculpture, painting, architecture and music.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Walter Winans won the gold medal for his sculpture, *An American Trotter*, which added to his previous gold medal for the running deer (double shot) competition at the 1908 Olympics and the silver medal in the running deer competition in 1912.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Baron Pierre de Coubertin, President of the IOC and founder of the modern Olympic movement, won the gold medal for literature.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] He actually entered the competition under the pseudonyms of Georges Hohrod and Martin Eschbach from Germany.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] With the exception of the sculpture competition, only gold medals were issued.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Italian Riccardo Barthelemy won the medal for music with his *Olympic Triumphal March*, and fellow countryman Giovanni Pellegrini won the gold for painting.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Swiss architects Eugène-Edouard Monod and Alphonse Laverrière shared the gold for their stadium design.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The sole silver medal, for sculpture, went to Frenchman Georges Dubois for his *Model of the entrance to a modern stadium*.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] In the evening of 7 July, demonstrations took place in the Olympic Stadium of sports from the Swedish island of Gotland.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] These began at 7:30pm with a demonstration of Pärk, a type of tennis with seven players a side.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] At the same time, at the other end of the stadium, a type of Icelandic wrestling called Glima was demonstrated.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Once those displays had concluded, further demonstrations were made of the Swedish sport varpa, similar to quoits, and stångstörtning, a version of the caber toss.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The three disciplines showcased were pärk, varpa and stångstörtning.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Baseball was also demonstrated at the Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] A game was played between the United States, the nation where the game was developed, and Sweden, the host nation.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The game was held on Monday, 15 July 1912 and started at 10 a.m. on the Ostermalm Athletic Grounds in Stockholm.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The Americans were represented by various members of the American Olympic track and field athletics delegation, while the Swedish team was the Vesterås Baseball Club, which had been formed in 1910 as the first baseball club in Sweden.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Four of the Americans played for Sweden, as the Swedish pitchers and catchers were inexperienced.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] One Swede eventually relieved Adams and Nelson, the American pitchers.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Six innings were played, with the Americans not batting in the sixth and allowing the Swedes to have six outs in their half of the inning.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The game was umpired by George Wright, a retired American National League baseball player.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Twenty-eight nations competed at the 1912 Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Egypt participated for the first time, as did Luxembourg, Iceland, Portugal, and Serbia.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Japan also made their Olympic debut, marking the first appearance of an Asian country at an Olympic Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Chile made its first appearance as a national team, with fourteen athletes attending the Games, although it had previously entered one individual at the 1896 Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] This was also the first time that athletes from Armenia had competed in the Olympics, as part of the team from Turkey (the officially recognised name for the Ottoman Empire).
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Serbia's appearance was the only time it attended an Olympic Games as an independent nation until the 2008 Summer Olympics, almost one hundred years later.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The only nation that participated in the previous games in London 1908 but was absent in Stockholm 1912 was Argentina.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality they were two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] At the time, Australasia (Australia and New Zealand), Canada and South Africa were all part of the British Empire.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Egypt was de jure under the control of Turkey, but had been de facto run by the British since 1882.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] This was the last Olympics that allowed "private entries", i.e. individual athletes that were not part of a country's officially selected team.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] Arnold Jackson was one such private entry; he won the 1500 metres by 0.1 seconds, ahead of an American trio, in what was acclaimed at the time to be "the greatest race ever run".
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] His medal is still credited to the United Kingdom, however.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] These are the top 10 nations that won medals at the 1912 Games.
[src:barcelona/1912-summer-olympics] The medals themselves included solid gold medals, the last time these were given out.
[src:barcelona/34] The **Spanish telephone numbering plan** is the allocation of telephone numbers in Spain.
[src:barcelona/34] It was previously regulated by the Comisión del Mercado de las Telecomunicaciones (CMT), but is now regulated by the Comisión Nacional de los Mercados y la Competencia (CNMC).
[src:barcelona/34] International calls were made by dialling the international access code **07**, waiting for a tone, and then dialling the country code.
[src:barcelona/34] It was also possible to call Andorra from other countries via Spain using the prefix +34 738 instead of via France using the prefix +33 628.
[src:barcelona/34] On 1 December 1998, Spain changed to a new telephone numbering plan.
[src:barcelona/34] Spain's international access code also changed from **07** to **00**, but this did not affect dialling arrangements for calls to Gibraltar, with the 9567 prefix being retained.
[src:barcelona/34] In addition, it was possible to call Gibraltar from other countries via Spain using the prefix +34 9567.
[src:barcelona/34] However, on 10 February 2007, Spain adopted the international prefix 00350 for all calls to Gibraltar, thereby bringing end to a dispute between Gibraltar and Spain.
[src:barcelona/34] Consequently, numbers with the prefix 9567 were withdrawn from use, and made available for reassignment to subscribers in Spain.
[src:barcelona/34] Mobile phone numbers begin with 6 or 7, followed by 8 digits (6xx xxx xxx or 7yx xxx xxx), where y can be 1 to 9, not 0 (zero).
[src:barcelona/34] Note, numbers starting with 70 are personal numbers which can be re-directed to any other number by the personal owner.
[src:barcelona/34] Since the blocks of mobile phone numbers are allocated according to demand from the service providers, there is not necessarily a unique service provider indicated by the three digit numbering group (6xx or 7yx).
[src:barcelona/34] Personal numbers are used as redirection IDs.
[src:barcelona/34] The owner of a personal number may request, for example, any call to its personal number to be redirected to any other number it wants.
[src:barcelona/34] Personal numbers begin with 5, followed by 8 digits.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] According to tradition, Barcelona was founded by either the Phoenicians or the Carthaginians, who had trading posts along the Catalonian coast.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In the Middle Ages, Barcelona became the capital of the County of Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona became the centre of Catalan separatism, briefly becoming part of France during the 17th century Reapers' War and again in 1812 until 1814 under Napoleon.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] After the Spanish transition to democracy in the 1970s, Barcelona once again became the capital of an autonomous Catalonia.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona has a rich cultural heritage and is today an important cultural centre and a major tourist destination.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Particularly renowned are the architectural works of Antoni Gaudí and Lluís Domènech i Montaner, which have been designated UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The city is home to two of the most prestigious universities in Spain: the University of Barcelona and Pompeu Fabra University.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The headquarters of the Union for the Mediterranean are located in Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The city is known for hosting the 1992 Summer Olympics as well as world-class conferences and expositions.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In addition, many international sport tournaments have been played here.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona is a major cultural, economic, and financial centre in southwestern Europe, as well as the main biotech hub in Spain.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] As a leading world city, Barcelona's influence in global socio-economic affairs qualifies it for global city status (Beta +).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Other sources suggest that the city may have been named after the Carthaginian general Hamilcar Barca, who was supposed to have founded the city in the 3rd century BC, but there is no evidence that its name in antiquity, *Barcino*, was connected with the Barcid family of Hamilcar.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] During the Middle Ages, the city was variously known as *Barchinona*, *Barçalona*, *Barchelonaa*, and *Barchenona*.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] An abbreviated form sometimes used by locals for the city is *Barna*.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] *Barça* is only applied to the local football club FC Barcelona, not to the city.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Another common abbreviation is 'BCN', which is also the IATA airport code of the Barcelona-El Prat Airport.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The city is referred to as the *Ciutat Comtal* in Catalan and *Ciudad Condal* in Spanish (i.e., "Comital City" or "City of Counts"), owing to its past as the seat of the Count of Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The origin of the earliest settlement at the site of present-day Barcelona is unclear.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The ruins of an early settlement have been found, including different tombs and dwellings dating to earlier than 5000 BC.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In Greek mythology, the founding of Barcelona had been attributed to the mythological Hercules.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] According to tradition, Barcelona was founded by Punic (Phoenician) settlers, who had trading posts along the Catalonian coast.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In particular, some historians attribute the foundation of the city directly to the historical Carthaginian general, Hamilcar Barca, father of Hannibal, who supposedly named the city *Barcino* after his family in the 3rd century BC, but this theory has been questioned.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Iberia and Barcelona was controlled by the Carthaginian Empire and was an important location for trade due to its proximity to Punic Ibiza.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Archeological evidence in the form of coins from the 3rd century BC have been found on the hills at the foot of Montjuïc with the name Bárkeno written in the Iberian script in the Iberian language.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In about 15 BC, the Romans redrew the town as a *castrum* (Roman military camp) centred on the "*Mons Taber*", a little hill near the Generalitat (Catalan Government) and city hall buildings.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The Roman Forum, at the crossing of the Cardo Maximus and Decumanus Maximus, was approximately placed where current Plaça de Sant Jaume is.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Thus, the political centre of the city, Catalonia, and its domains has remained in the same place for over 2,000 years.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Under the Romans, it was a colony with the surname of *Faventia*, or, in full, *Colonia Faventia Julia Augusta Pia Barcino* or *Colonia Julia Augusta Faventia Paterna Barcino*.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] It enjoyed immunity from imperial burdens.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The city minted its own coins; some from the era of Galba survive.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Important Roman vestiges are displayed in Plaça del Rei underground, as a part of the Barcelona City History Museum (MUHBA); the typically Roman grid plan is still visible today in the layout of the historical centre, the *Barri Gòtic* (Gothic Quarter).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Some remaining fragments of the Roman walls have been incorporated into the cathedral.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The cathedral, Catedral Basílica Metropolitana de Barcelona, is also sometimes called *La Seu*, which simply means cathedral (and see, among other things) in Catalan.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The city was conquered by the Visigoths in the early 5th century, becoming for a few years the capital of all Hispania.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] After being conquered by the Umayyads in the early 8th century, it was conquered after a siege in 801 by Charlemagne's son Louis, who made Barcelona the seat of the Carolingian "Hispanic March" (*Marca Hispanica*), a buffer zone ruled by the Count of Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The Counts of Barcelona became increasingly independent and expanded their territory to include much of modern Catalonia, although in 985, Barcelona was sacked by the army of Almanzor.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The sack was so traumatic that most of Barcelona's population was either killed or enslaved.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 1137, Aragon and the County of Barcelona merged in dynastic union by the marriage of Ramon Berenguer IV and Petronilla of Aragon, their titles finally borne by only one person when their son Alfonso II of Aragon ascended to the throne in 1162.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] His territories were later to be known as the Crown of Aragon, which conquered many overseas possessions and ruled the western Mediterranean Sea with outlying territories in Naples and Sicily and as far as Athens in the 13th century.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona also had a substantial Jewish community at the time, then the largest Jewish community in the Crown of Aragon.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Called "the Call," for the many small streets that defined the area, it later became enclosed.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Montjuïc or Montjuich, in medieval Latin and Catalan, meaning "Jewish Mountain" and the birthplace of the city, is the site of a medieval Jewish cemetery, Jews continued to live in Barcelona until the Massacre of 1391 diminished their numbers.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The Spanish Inquisition forced the remaining Jews who refused to convert to Christianity to be burned at the stake, or sell their property and leave.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was the leading slave trade centre of the Crown of Aragon up until the 15th century, when it was eclipsed by Valencia.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] It initially fed from eastern and Balkan slave stock later drawing from a Maghribian and, ultimately, Subsaharan pool of slaves.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The Bank or Taula de canvi de Barcelona, often viewed as the oldest public bank in Europe, was established by the city magistrates in 1401.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] It originated from necessities of the state, as did the Bank of Venice (1402) and the Bank of Genoa (1407).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In the beginning of the early modern period, Barcelona lost political primacy, but the economy managed to achieve a balance between production capacity and imports.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In the context of the wider early recovery of Catalonia from the 17th-century crisis in the second half of the century, increasing maritime activity since 1675 doubled traffic in the port of Barcelona compared to figures from the beginning of the 17th century.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In the late 17th and early 18th century, Barcelona repeatedly endured the effects of war, including the 1691 bombing, the sieges of 1697, 1704, 1705, 1706, and the 1713 blockade and ensuing 1714 siege and assault.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In the 18th century, the population grew from 30,000 to about 100,000 inhabitants, as the city became one of the key mercantile centres in the Western Mediterranean, with inland influence up to Zaragoza, and to the south up to Alicante.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] A fortress was built at Montjuïc that overlooked the harbour.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Much of Barcelona was negatively affected by the Napoleonic wars, but the start of industrialization saw the fortunes of the province improve.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] During the 19th century, Catalan business interests, many of them based in Barcelona, became increasingly involved in the Atlantic slave trade, taking advantage of the void left by the British abolition of the trade in 1807.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Catalan immigrants in Spanish America also became heavily involved in owning and running slave plantations in Cuba and Puerto Rico.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] When slavery was abolished in the Spanish Empire in 1886, many Catalans returned to Barcelona and invested their newfound fortunes in constructing opulent mansions in areas such as La Rambla.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In the mid-1850s, Barcelona was struggling with population density as it became an industrial, port city and European capital.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The city's density was at 856 people per hectare, more than double that of Paris.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Mortality rates were on the rise and any outbreaks of disease would devastate the population.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] To solve the issue, a civil engineer named Ildefons Cerdà proposed a plan for a new district known as the Eixample.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The citizens of Barcelona had begun to demolish the medieval wall surrounding and constricting the city.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Cerdà thought it best to transform the land outside the walls into an area characterized by a scientific approach to urbanization.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] His proposal consisted of a grid of streets to unite the old city and surrounding villages.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] There would also be wide streets to allow people to breathe clean air, gardens in the centre of each street block, integration of rich and poor giving both groups access to the same services, and smooth-flowing traffic.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Urban quality, egalitarianism, hygiene, sunlight, and efficiency were all major keys for Cerdà's vision.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Not everything he imagined would be realized within the Eixample district, but the iconic octagonal superblocks with chamfered corners for better visibility are his direct brainchild and remain immensely helpful even 170 years later.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The district and its ideals were not appreciated at the time.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The city council awarded the design of the extension plan to another architect.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The Spanish government was the one to step in and impose Cerdà's plan, laying the groundwork for many more tensions between the Spanish and Catalan administrations.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Regardless, some of the upper class citizens of Barcelona were excited by the new plan and began a race to build "the biggest, tallest, most attractive house" in the district.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Their interest and money fueled the rich diversity that we now see in the district's architecture.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In the end, Cerdà's ideas would have a lasting impact on Barcelona's development, earning it international recognition for its highly efficient approach to urban planning and design.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Shortly after the establishment of the Second Spanish Republic, in 1931, it became the capital of the autonomous region of Catalonia.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] During the Spanish Civil War, the city, and Catalonia in general, were resolutely Republican.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Many enterprises and public services were collectivized by the CNT and UGT unions.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] As the power of the Republican government and the Generalitat diminished, much of the city was under the effective control of anarchist groups.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The anarchists lost control of the city to their own allies, the Communists and official government troops, after the street fighting of the Barcelona May Days.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was one of the last places in Spain to fall under Francoist control, and became the capital of the Second Spanish Republic in November 1937.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] From 16 to 18 March 1938, Barcelona was bombed several times by Fascist Italy and Nazi Germany, in support of the Francoist-led army.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] It left at least 1,300 people killed and 2,000 wounded.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The airstrikes intended to destroy industrial areas and demoralize the republicans, however civil buildings were also destroyed.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The fall of the city on 26 January 1939, caused a mass exodus of civilians who fled to the French border.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The resistance of Barcelona to Franco's *coup d'état* was to have lasting effects after the defeat of the Republican government.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The autonomous institutions of Catalonia were abolished, and the use of the Catalan language in public life was suppressed.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona remained the second largest city in Spain, at the heart of a region which was relatively industrialized and prosperous, despite the devastation of the civil war.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The result was a large-scale immigration from poorer regions of Spain (particularly Andalusia, Murcia and Galicia), which in turn led to rapid urbanization.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] During the francoist period, municipal elections were suspended through all Spain and the mayor was appointed by the central government.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Pressure for change was particularly strong in Barcelona, which considered that it had been punished during nearly forty years of Francoism for its support of the Republican government.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] After Franco's death in 1975, massive peaceful demonstrations on 11 September 1977 assembled over a million people in the streets of Barcelona to call for the restoration of Catalan autonomy.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] After the adoption of the Constitution, municipal elections were held again (1979).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The development of Barcelona was promoted by two events in 1986: Spanish accession to the European Community, and particularly Barcelona's designation as host city of the 1992 Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The process of urban regeneration has been rapid, and accompanied by a greatly increased international reputation of the city as a tourist destination.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The increased cost of housing has led to a slight decline (−16.6%) in the population over the last two decades of the 20th century as many families move out into the suburbs.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] This decline has been reversed since 2001, as a new wave of immigration (particularly from Latin America and from Morocco) has gathered pace.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 1987, an ETA car bombing at Hipercor killed 21 people.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 1992, Barcelona hosted the Summer Olympics.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The after-effects of this are credited with driving major changes in what had, up until then, been a largely industrial city.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] As part of the preparation for the games, industrial buildings along the sea-front were demolished and 3 km (2 mi) of beach were created.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] New construction increased the road capacity of the city by 17%, the sewage handling capacity by 27% and the amount of new green areas and beaches by 78%.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Between 1990 and 2004, the number of hotel rooms in the city doubled.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Perhaps more importantly, the outside perception of the city was changed making, by 2012, Barcelona the 12th most popular city destination in the world and the 5th amongst European cities.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The year 2017 was an intense year in Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] On August 17, Barcelona suffered a terrorist attack in the iconic Rambla, where a van drove into pedestrians, killing 13 people and injuring at least 130 others.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The perpetrator fled on foot, killing another person to steal his car, and a large police operation was started.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Massive demonstrations in the city center took place the days after the attack, with the motto "*No tinc por*" ("I am not afraid").
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Other attacks took place elsewhere in Catalonia.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The Prime Minister of Spain, Mariano Rajoy, called the attack in Barcelona a jihadist attack.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Amaq News Agency attributed indirect responsibility for the attack to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] On October 2017, after several years of growing of the Catalan independence movement, with massive demonstrations along the decade, an independence referendum took place.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] It was declared unconstitutional by the Spanish Constitutional Court, however the Catalan Government ignored it and celebrated it.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] This led to another court ordering the Spanish Civil Guard and National Police to dismantle voting centers, however their intervention was not pacific.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was the scenario of several police oppression and chaos, with sources that reported at least 1,066 injured requiring medical attention.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Several NGOs condemned the police's violence and reported an excessive use of force.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The referendum sparked the 2017–2018 Spanish constitutional crisis, and later protests took place.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In July 2023, Barcelona was announced as the UNESCO-UIA World Capital of Architecture for the 2024–2026 term.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] This means it will be the hub for discussion around global challenges including culture, heritage, urban planning and architecture.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In addition to being the capital through 2026, it will also host the UIA World Congress of Architects for that year.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The honour is befitting of Barcelona, as its history is peppered with architectural achievement and various iconic styles and influences.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] From its ancient Roman roots, to the Gothic and Modernisme movements, Barcelona has thrived through the way it ties together architecture and culture.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona is located on the northeast coast of the Iberian Peninsula, facing the Mediterranean Sea, on a plain approximately 5 km (3 mi) wide limited by the mountain range of Collserola, the Llobregat river to the southwest and the Besòs river to the north.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] This plain covers an area of 170 km2 (66 sq mi), of which 101 km2 (39.0 sq mi) are occupied by the city itself.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] It is 120 km (75 mi) south of the Pyrenees and the Catalan border with France.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Tibidabo, 512 m (1,680 ft) high, offers striking views over the city and is topped by the 288.4 m (946.2 ft) Torre de Collserola, a telecommunications tower that is visible from most of the city.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona is peppered with small hills, most of them urbanized, that gave their name to the neighbourhoods built upon them, such as Carmel (267 m or 876 ft), Putxet (es) (181 m or 594 ft) and Rovira (261 m or 856 ft).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The escarpment of Montjuïc (173 m or 568 ft), situated to the southeast, overlooks the harbour and is topped by Montjuïc Castle, a fortress built in the 17–18th centuries to control the city as a replacement for the Ciutadella.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Today, the fortress is a museum and Montjuïc is home to several sporting and cultural venues, as well as Barcelona's biggest park and gardens.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The municipality includes two small sparsely-inhabited exclaves to the north-west.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification, Barcelona has a hot summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*), with mild winters and warm to hot summers, while the rainiest seasons are autumn and spring.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The rainfall pattern is characterized by a short (3 months) dry season in summer, as well as less winter rainfall than in a typical Mediterranean climate.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] However, both June and August are wetter than February, which is unusual for the Mediterranean climate.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] This subtype, labelled as "Portuguese" by the French geographer George Viers after the climate classification of Emmanuel de Martonne and found in the NW Mediterranean area (e.g.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Marseille), can be seen as transitional to the humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*) found in inland areas.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona is densely populated, thus heavily influenced by the urban heat island effect.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Areas outside of the urbanized districts can have as much as 2 °C of difference in temperatures throughout the year.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Its average annual temperature is 21.2 °C (70.2 °F) during the day and 15.1 °C (59.2 °F) at night.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The average annual temperature of the sea is about 20 °C (68 °F).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In the coldest month, January, the temperature typically ranges from 12 to 18 °C (54 to 64 °F) during the day, 6 to 12 °C (43 to 54 °F) at night and the average sea temperature is 13 °C (55 °F).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In the warmest month, August, the typical temperature ranges from 27 to 31 °C (81 to 88 °F) during the day, about 23 °C (73 °F) at night and the average sea temperature is 26 °C (79 °F).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Generally, the summer or "holiday" season lasts about six months, from May to October.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Two months – April and November – are transitional; sometimes the temperature exceeds 20 °C (68 °F), with an average temperature of 18–19 °C (64–66 °F) during the day and 11–13 °C (52–55 °F) at night.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] December, January and February are the coldest months, with average temperatures around 15 °C (59 °F) during the day and 9 °C (48 °F) at night.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Large fluctuations in temperature are rare, particularly in the summer months.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Because of the proximity to the warm sea plus the urban heat island, frosts are very rare in the city of Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Snow is also very infrequent in the city of Barcelona, but light snowfalls can occur yearly in the nearby Collserola mountains, such as in the Fabra Observatory located in a nearby mountain.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona averages 78 rainy days per year (≥ 1 mm), and annual average relative humidity is 72%, ranging from 69% in July to 75% in October.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Rainfall totals are highest in late summer and autumn (September–November) and lowest in early and mid-summer (June–August), with a secondary winter minimum (February–March).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Sunshine duration is 2,524 hours per year, from 138 (average 4.5 hours of sunshine a day) in December to 310 (average 10 hours of sunshine a day) in July.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] It is the main component of an administrative area of Greater Barcelona, with a population of 3,218,071 in an area of 636 km2 (246 sq mi) (density 5,060 inhabitants/km2).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The population of the urban area was 4,840,000.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] It is the central nucleus of the Barcelona metropolitan area, which relies on a population of 5,474,482.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 1900, Barcelona had a population of 533,000, which grew steadily but slowly until 1950, when it started absorbing a high number of people from other less-industrialized parts of Spain.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona's population peaked in 1979 at 1,906,998, and fell throughout the 1980s and 1990s as more people sought a higher quality of life in outlying cities in the Barcelona Metropolitan Area.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] After bottoming out in 2000 with 1,496,266 residents, the city's population began to rise again as younger people started to return, causing a great increase in housing prices.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Catalan is the "own language" of Catalonia and Barcelona, and therefore its the main language used by the City Council, in schools and it dominates the linguistic landscape.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] All toponymy of Barcelona, including the stops of the metro system, are exclusively in the Catalan language.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Despite this, Spanish is the most spoken language in Barcelona (according to the linguistic census held by the Government of Catalonia in 2013) and it is understood almost universally.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Catalan is also very commonly spoken in the city: it is understood by 95% of the population, while 72.3% can speak it, 79% can read it, and 53% can write it.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Knowledge of Catalan has increased significantly in recent decades thanks to a language immersion educational system.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] After Catalan and Spanish, the most spoken languages in Barcelona are those from North Africa, such as Amazigh and Arabic, followed by Bengali, Urdu, Punjabi, Mandarin Chinese, Romanian, English, Russian and Quechua, according to data collected by the University of Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona is one of the most densely populated cities in Europe.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 2008, the city council calculated the population to 1,621,090 living in the 102.2 km2 sized municipality, giving the city an average population density of 15,926 inhabitants per square kilometre with Eixample being the most populated district.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In the case of Barcelona though, the land distribution is extremely uneven.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Half of the municipality or 50.2 km2, all of it located on the municipal edge is made up of the ten least densely populated neighbourhoods containing less than 10% of the city's population, the uninhabited Zona Franca industrial area and Montjuïc forest park.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Leaving the remaining 90% or slightly below 1.5 million inhabitants living on the remaining 52 km2 (20 sq mi) at an average density close to 28,500 inhabitants per square kilometre.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Of the 73 neighbourhoods in the city, 45 had a population density above 20,000 inhabitants per square kilometre with a combined population of 1,313,424 inhabitants living on 38.6 km2 at an average density of 33,987 inhabitants per square kilometre.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The 30 most densely populated neighbourhoods accounted for 57.5% of the city population occupying only 22.7% of the municipality, or in other words, 936,406 people living at an average density of 40,322 inhabitants per square kilometre.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The city's highest density is found at and around the neighbourhood of la Sagrada Família where four of the city's most densely populated neighbourhoods are located side by side, all with a population density above 50,000 inhabitants per square kilometre.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 1900, almost a third (28.9 percent) of the population were children (aged younger than 14 years).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 2017, this age group constituted only 12.7% of the population.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 2017, people aged between 15 and 24 years made up 9 percent of the population; those aged between 25 and 44 years made up 30.6 percent of the population; while those aged between 45 and 64 years formed 56.9% of all Barcelonans.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 1900, people aged 65 and older made up just 6.5 percent of the population.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 2017, this age group made up 21.5 percent of the population.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 2016, about 59% of the inhabitants of the city were born in Catalonia and 18.5% coming from the rest of the country.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In addition to that, 22.5% of the population was born outside of Spain, a proportion which has more than doubled since 2001 and more than quintupled since 1996 when it was 8.6% and 3.9% respectively.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The most important region of origin of migrants is Europe, with many coming from Italy (26,676) or France (13,506).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Moreover, many migrants come from Latin American nations such as Bolivia, Ecuador or Colombia.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Since the 1990s, and similar to other migrants, many Latin Americans have settled in northern parts of the city.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] There exists a relatively large Pakistani community in Barcelona with up to twenty thousand nationals.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The community consists of significantly more men than women.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Many of the Pakistanis are living in Ciutat Vella.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] First Pakistani migrants came in the 1970s, with increasing numbers in the 1990s.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Other significant migrant groups come from Asia as from China and the Philippines.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] There is a Japanese community clustered in Bonanova, Les Tres Torres, Pedralbes, and other northern neighbourhoods, and a Japanese international school serves that community.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 2007, most of the inhabitants stated they are Roman Catholic (208 churches).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In a 2011 survey conducted by InfoCatólica, 49.5% of Barcelona residents of all ages identified themselves as Catholic.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] This was the first time that more than half of respondents did not identify themselves as Catholic Christians.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The numbers reflect a broader trend in Spain whereby the numbers of self-identified Catholics have declined.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 2019, a survey by Centro de Investigaciones Sociológicas showed that 53.2% of residents in Barcelona identified themselves as Catholic (9.9% practising Catholics, 43.3% non-practising Catholics).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The province has the largest Muslim community in Spain, 322,698 people in Barcelona province are of Muslim religion.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] A considerable number of Muslims live in Barcelona due to immigration (169 locations, mostly professed by Moroccans in Spain).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 2014, 322,698 out of 5.5 million people in the province of Barcelona identified themselves as Muslim, which makes 5.6% of the total population.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The city also has the largest Jewish community in Spain, with an estimated 3,500 Jews living in the city.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] There are also a number of other groups, including Evangelical (71 locations, mostly professed by Roma), Jehovah's Witnesses (21 Kingdom Halls), Buddhists (13 locations), and Eastern Orthodox.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The Barcelona metropolitan area comprises over 66% of the people of Catalonia, one of the richer regions in Europe and the fourth richest region per capita in Spain, with a GDP per capita amounting to €28,400 (16% more than the EU average).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The greater Barcelona metropolitan area had a GDP amounting to $177 billion (equivalent to $34,821 in per capita terms, 44% more than the EU average), making it the 4th most economically powerful city by gross GDP in the European Union, and 35th in the world in 2009.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona city had a very high GDP of €80,894 per head in 2004, according to Eurostat.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Furthermore, Barcelona was Europe's fourth best business city and fastest improving European city, with growth improved by 17% per year as of 2009.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was the 24th most "livable city" in the world in 2015 according to lifestyle magazine *Monocle*.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Similarly, according to Innovation Analysts 2thinknow, Barcelona occupies 13th place in the world on *Innovation Cities™ Global Index*.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] At the same time it is according to the Global Wealth and Lifestyle Report 2020 one of the most affordable cities in the world for a luxury lifestyle.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona has a long-standing mercantile tradition.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Less well known is that the city industrialized early, taking off in 1833, when Catalonia's already sophisticated textile industry began to use steam power.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] It became the first and most important industrial city in the Mediterranean basin.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Since then, manufacturing has played a large role in its history.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Borsa de Barcelona (Barcelona Stock Exchange) is the main stock exchange in the northeastern part of the Iberian Peninsula.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was recognized as the Southern European City of the Future for 2014/15, based on its economic potential, by *FDi Magazine* in their bi-annual rankings.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] It also has several congress halls, notably Fira de Barcelona – the second largest trade fair and exhibition centre in Europe, that host a quickly growing number of national and international events each year (at present above 50).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The total exhibition floor space of Fira de Barcelona venues is 405,000 m2 (41 ha), not counting Gran Via centre on the Plaza de Europa.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] However, the Eurozone crisis and deep cuts in business travel affected the council's positioning of the city as a convention centre.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] An important business centre, the World Trade Center Barcelona, is located in Barcelona's Port Vell harbour.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The city is known for hosting well as world-class conferences and expositions, including the 1888 *Exposición Universal de Barcelona*, the 1929 Barcelona International Exposition (Expo 1929), the 2004 Universal Forum of Cultures and the 2004 World Urban Forum.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In 2023, Barcelona was the 9th most visited city in the world by international visitors and the fifth most visited city in Europe after Paris, Madrid, Amsterdam, and Rome, with around 9 million international arrivals.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Due to its large influx of tourists each year, Barcelona, like many other tourism capitals, has to deal with pickpockets, with wallets and passports being commonly stolen items.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] While tourism produces economic benefits, according to one report, the city is "overrun [by] hordes of tourists".
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In early 2017, over 150,000 protesters warned that tourism is destabilizing the city.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Slogans included "Tourists go home", "Barcelona is not for sale" and "We will not be driven out".
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] By then, the number of visitors had increased from 1.7 million in 1990 to 32 million in a city with a population of 1.62 million, increasing the cost of rental housing for residents and overcrowding the public places.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] While tourists spent an estimated €30 billion in 2017, they are viewed by some as a threat to Barcelona's identity.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] A May 2017 article in the British online daily *The Independent* included Barcelona among the "Eight Places That Hate Tourists the Most" and included a comment from Mayor Ada Colau, "We don't want the city to become a cheap souvenir shop", citing Venice as an example.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] To moderate the problem, the city has stopped issuing licenses for new hotels and holiday apartments; it also fined AirBnb €30,000.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The mayor has suggested introducing a new tourist tax and setting a limit on the number of visitors.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] One industry insider, Justin Francis, founder of the Responsible Travel agency, stated that steps must be taken to limit the number of visitors that are causing an "overtourism crisis" in several major European cities.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] "Ultimately, residents must be prioritised over tourists for housing, infrastructure and access to services because they have a long-term stake in the city's success", he said.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] "Managing tourism more responsibly can help", Francis later told a journalist, "but some destinations may just have too many tourists, and Barcelona may be a case of that".
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] In April 2024 protests against overtourism began in the city, reaching its peak in July 2024.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] These protests caught further attention again in July 2025, as similar protests took place in Southern Europe and included Palma, and Lisbon, organized by the Southern Europe Network Against Touristification (SET).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] During the protests some protesters used large water guns to spray water on tourists.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Industry generates 21% of the total gross domestic product (GDP) of the region, with the energy, chemical and metallurgy industries accounting for 47% of industrial production.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The Barcelona metropolitan area had 67% of the total number of industrial establishments in Catalonia as of 1997.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona has long been an important European automobile manufacturing centre.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Formerly there were automobile factories of AFA, Abadal, Actividades Industriales, Alvarez, America, Artés de Arcos, Balandrás, Baradat-Esteve, Biscúter, J.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Today, the headquarters and a large factory of SEAT (the largest Spanish automobile manufacturer) are in one of its suburbs.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] There is also a Nissan factory in the logistics and industrial area of the city.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The factory of Derbi, a large manufacturer of motorcycles, scooters and mopeds, also lies near the city.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] As in other modern cities, the manufacturing sector has long since been overtaken by the services sector, though it remains very important.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The region's leading industries are textiles, chemical, pharmaceutical, motor, electronic, printing, logistics, publishing, in telecommunications industry and culture the notable Mobile World Congress, and information technology services.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The traditional importance of textiles is reflected in Barcelona's drive to become a major fashion centre.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] There have been many attempts to launch Barcelona as a fashion capital, notably *Gaudi Home*.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Beginning in the summer of 2000, the city hosted the Bread & Butter urban fashion fair until 2009, when its organizers announced that it would be returning to Berlin.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] This was a hard blow for the city as the fair brought €100 m to the city in just three days.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] From 2009, *The Brandery*, an urban fashion show, was held in Barcelona twice a year until 2012.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] According to the Global Language Monitor's annual ranking of the world's top fifty fashion capitals Barcelona was named as the seventh most important fashion capital of the world right after Milan and before Berlin in 2015.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Several technology companies have offices in Barcelona, most of them in the El Poblenou neighborhood.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Examples of technology companies based in Barcelona: Factorial (software company), Glovo, TravelPerk, Wallapop, EDreams.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Technology companies not based in Barcelona but having an office in the city include Oracle Corporation, Amazon (company), King (company), Dynatrace, Clarivate, Ocado, Sage Group, Smallpdf, Proton Mail, Hewlett-Packard, Personio, Semrush.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was ranked as the number 1 startup hub in Southern Europe, and as the 33rd best city in the Global Started Ecosystem published by Startupblink.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p01] The Barcelona Supercomputing Center is located in Barcelona and hosts the MareNostrum supercomputer.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] As the capital of the autonomous community of Catalonia, Barcelona is the seat of the Catalan government, known as the *Generalitat de Catalunya*; of particular note are the executive branch, the parliament, and the High Court of Justice of Catalonia.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The city is also the capital of the Province of Barcelona and the Barcelonès comarca (district).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is governed by a city council formed by 41 city councillors, elected for a four-year term by universal suffrage.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] As one of the two biggest cities in Spain, Barcelona is subject to a special law articulated through the *Carta Municipal* (Municipal Law).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] A first version of this law was passed in 1960 and amended later, but the current version was approved in March 2006.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] According to this law, Barcelona's city council is organized in two levels: a political one, with elected city councillors, and one executive, which administers the programs and executes the decisions taken on the political level.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] This law also gives the local government a special relationship with the central government and it also gives the mayor wider prerogatives by the means of municipal executive commissions.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It expands the powers of the city council in areas like telecommunications, city traffic, road safety and public safety.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It also gives a special economic regime to the city's treasury and it gives the council a veto in matters that will be decided by the central government, but that will need a favourable report from the council.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The *Comissió de Govern* (Government Commission) is the executive branch, formed by 24 councillors, led by the Mayor, with 5 lieutenant-mayors and 17 city councillors, each in charge of an area of government, and 5 non-elected councillors.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The plenary, formed by the 41 city councillors, has advisory, planning, regulatory, and fiscal executive functions.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The six *Commissions del Consell Municipal* (City council commissions) have executive and controlling functions in the field of their jurisdiction.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] They are composed by a number of councillors proportional to the number of councillors each political party has in the plenary.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Some of these competencies are not exclusive, but shared with the Generalitat de Catalunya or the central Spanish government.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] In some fields with shared responsibility (such as public health, education or social services), there is a shared Agency or Consortium between the city and the Generalitat to plan and manage services.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The executive branch is led by a Chief Municipal Executive Officer which answers to the Mayor.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It is made up of departments which are legally part of the city council and by separate legal entities of two types: autonomous public departments and public enterprises.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The seat of the city council is on the Plaça de Sant Jaume, opposite the seat of Generalitat de Catalunya.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Since the coming of the Spanish democracy, Barcelona had been governed by the PSC, first with an absolute majority and later in coalition with ERC and ICV.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] After the May 2007 election, the ERC did not renew the coalition agreement and the PSC governed in a minority coalition with ICV as the junior partner.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] After 32 years, on 22 May 2011, CiU gained a plurality of seats at the municipal election, gaining 15 seats to the PSC's 11.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Public safety in Barcelona is the duty of the City Council and the Government of Catalonia, who provide it through 2 police forces: the *Guàrdia Urbana de Barcelona* and the *Mossos d'Esquadra*, respectively.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Before 2008, public safety was also conducted by the National Police Corps, however their duties are now delegated to documental and immigration purposes.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Medical emergencies are attended by the System of Medical Emergencies, while fire and rescue emergencies are attended by the *Bombers de Barcelona*.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Maritime rescue is provided by the Maritime Safety and Rescue Society, the Civil Guard and *Mossos* (with the support of *Guàrdia Urbana* during the summer).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The protection of the wildlife of the part of Collserola Park inside municipal limits is the duty of the Rural Agents Corps.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The districts are based mostly on historical divisions, and several are former towns annexed by the city of Barcelona in the 18th and 19th centuries that still maintain their own distinct character.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Each district has its own council led by a city councillor.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The composition of each district council depends on the number of votes each political party had in that district, so a district can be led by a councillor from a different party than the executive council.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona has a well-developed higher education system of public universities.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Most prominent among these are the University of Barcelona (established in 1450) and the more modern Pompeu Fabra University.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is also home to the Polytechnic University of Catalonia, and in the private sector the EADA Business School (founded in 1957), which became the first Barcelona institution to run manager training programmes for the business community.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] IESE Business School, as well as the largest private educational institution, the Ramon Llull University, which encompasses schools and institutes such as the ESADE Business School.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The Autonomous University of Barcelona, another public university, is located in Bellaterra, a town in the Metropolitan Area.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Toulouse Business School and the Open University of Catalonia (a private Internet-centred open university) are also based in Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The city has a network of public schools, from nurseries to high schools, under the responsibility of a consortium led by city council (though the curriculum is the responsibility of the Generalitat de Catalunya).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] There are also many private schools, some of them Roman Catholic.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Most such schools receive a public subsidy on a per-student basis, are subject to inspection by the public authorities, and are required to follow the same curricular guidelines as public schools, though they charge tuition.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Known as *escoles concertades*, they are distinct from schools whose funding is entirely private (*escoles privades*).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The language of instruction at public schools and *escoles concertades* is Catalan, as stipulated by the 2009 Catalan Education Act.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Spanish may be used as a language of instruction by teachers of Spanish literature or language, and foreign languages by teachers of those languages.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] An experimental partial immersion programme adopted by some schools allows for the teaching of a foreign language (English, generally) across the curriculum, though this is limited to a maximum of 30% of the school day.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] No public school or *escola concertada* in Barcelona may offer 50% or full immersion programmes in a foreign language, nor does any public school or *escola concertada* offer International Baccalaureate programmes.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona's cultural roots go back 2000 years.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Since the arrival of democracy, the Catalan language (very much repressed during the dictatorship of Franco) has been promoted, both by recovering works from the past and by stimulating the creation of new works.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is designated as a world-class city by the Globalization and World Cities Study Group and Network.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It has also been part of the UNESCO Creative Cities Network as a City of Literature since 2015.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona has many venues for live music and theatre, including the world-renowned Gran Teatre del Liceu opera house, the Teatre Nacional de Catalunya, the Teatre Lliure and the Palau de la Música Catalana concert hall.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona also is home to the Barcelona Symphony and Catalonia National Orchestra (Orquestra Simfònica de Barcelona i Nacional de Catalunya, usually known as OBC), the largest symphonic orchestra in Catalonia.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] In 1999, the OBC inaugurated its new venue in the brand-new Auditorium (L'Auditori).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It performs around 75 concerts per season and its current director is Eiji Oue.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It is home to the Barcelona Guitar Orchestra, directed by Sergi Vicente.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The major thoroughfare of La Rambla is home to mime artists and street performers.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Yearly, two major pop music festivals take place in the city, the Sónar Festival and the Primavera Sound Festival.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The city also has a thriving alternative music scene, with groups such as The Pinker Tones receiving international attention.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is an international hub of highly active and diverse nightlife with bars, dance bars and nightclubs staying open well past midnight.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona's oldest and main online newspaper *VilaWeb* is also one of the oldest one in Europe (with Catalan and English editions).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Several major FM stations include Catalunya Ràdio, RAC 1, RAC 105 and Cadena SER.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona also has a local TV station, Betevé, owned by city council.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The headquarters of Televisió de Catalunya, Catalonia's public network, are located in Sant Joan Despí, in Barcelona's metropolitan area.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona has a long sporting tradition and hosted the highly successful 1992 Summer Olympics as well as several matches during the 1982 FIFA World Cup (at the two stadiums).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It has hosted about 30 sports events of international significance.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] FC Barcelona is a sports club best known worldwide for its football team, one of the largest and the wealthiest in the world.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It has 74 national trophies (while finishing 46 times as runners-up) and 17 continental prizes (with being runners-up 11 times), including five UEFA Champions League trophies out of eight finals and three FIFA Club World Cup wins out of four finals.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The club won six trophies in a calendar year in 2009, becoming one of only 2 male football teams in the world to win the coveted sextuple, apart from FC Bayern Munich in 2020.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The club's museum is the second most visited in Catalonia.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The matches against cross-town rivals RCD Espanyol are of particular interest, but there are other Barcelonan football clubs in lower categories, like CE Europa and UE Sant Andreu.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] FC Barcelona's basketball team has a noted rivalry in the Liga ACB with nearby Joventut Badalona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona has three UEFA elite stadiums: FC Barcelona's Camp Nou, the largest stadium in Europe with a capacity of 99,354; the publicly owned Estadi Olímpic Lluís Companys, with a capacity of 55,926; used for the 1992 Olympics; and Estadi Cornellà-El Prat, with a capacity of 40,500.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Furthermore, the city has several smaller stadiums such as Mini Estadi (also owned by FC Barcelona) with a capacity of 15,000, Camp Municipal Narcís Sala with a capacity of 6,563 and Nou Sardenya with a capacity of 7,000.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The city has a further three multifunctional venues for sports and concerts: the Palau Sant Jordi with a capacity of 12,000 to 24,000 (depending on use), the Palau Blaugrana with a capacity of 7,500, and the Palau dels Esports de Barcelona with a capacity of 3,500.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona was the host city for the 2013 World Aquatics Championships, which were held at the Palau San Jordi.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] There is also the Ultratrail Collserola which passes 85 km (53 mi) through the Collserola forest.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The Open Seat Godó, a 50-year-old ATP World Tour 500 Series tennis tournament, is held annually in the facilities of the Real Club de Tenis Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Each year on Christmas Day, a 200-meter swimming race across the Old Port of Barcelona takes place.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Near Barcelona, in Montmeló, the 107,000 capacity Circuit de Barcelona-Catalunya racetrack hosts the Formula One Spanish Grand Prix, the Catalan motorcycle Grand Prix, the Spanish GT Championship and races in the GP2 Series.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Skateboarding and cycling are also very popular in Barcelona; in and around the city there are dozens of kilometers of bicycle paths.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is also home to numerous social centres and illegal squats that effectively form a shadow society mainly made up of the unemployed, immigrants, dropouts, anarchists, anti-authoritarians and autonomists.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Peter Gelderloos estimates that there around 200 squatted buildings and 40 social centres across the city with thousands of inhabitants, making it one of the largest squatter movements in the world.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] He notes that they pirate electricity, internet and water allowing them to live on less than one euro a day.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] He argues that these squats embrace an anarcho-communist and anti-work philosophy, often freely fixing up new houses, cleaning, patching roofs, installing windows, toilets, showers, lights and kitchens.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The squats help elderly residents avoid eviction and organize various protests throughout Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Notable squats include Can Vies, Can Masdeu, La Cinètika, Àgora Juan Andrés Benítez and Kasa de la Muntanya.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is served by Barcelona-El Prat Airport, about 17 km (11 mi) south-west of the centre of Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It is the second-largest airport in Spain, and the largest on the Mediterranean coast, which handled more than 50.17 million passengers in 2018, showing an annual upward trend.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It is a main hub for Vueling Airlines and Ryanair, and also a focus for Iberia and Air Europa.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The airport mainly serves domestic and European destinations, although some airlines offer destinations in Latin America, Asia and the United States.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The airport is connected to the city by highway, metro (Airport T1 and Airport T2 stations), commuter train (Barcelona Airport railway station) and scheduled bus service.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] A new terminal (T1) has been built, and entered service on 17 June 2009.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Some low-cost airlines, also use Girona-Costa Brava Airport, about 90 km (56 mi) to the north, Reus Airport, 77 km (48 mi) to the south, or Lleida-Alguaire Airport, about 150 km (93 mi) to the west, of the city.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Sabadell Airport is a smaller airport in the nearby town of Sabadell, devoted to pilot training, aerotaxi and private flights.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The city has several heliports, mainly at the top of hospitals or tall buildings.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] However, only one heliport is public, the Port of Barcelona Heliport.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The Port of Barcelona has a 2000-year-old history and a great contemporary commercial importance.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] It is Europe's ninth largest container port, with a trade volume of 1.72 million TEU's in 2013.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The port is managed by the Port Authority of Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Its 10 km2 (4 sq mi) are divided into three zones: Port Vell (the old port), the commercial port and the logistics port (Barcelona Free Port).
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The port is undergoing an enlargement that will double its size thanks to diverting the mouth of the Llobregat river 2 km (1 mi) to the south.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The Barcelona harbour is the leading European cruiser port and a very important Mediterranean turnaround base.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] In 2013, 3.6 million pleasure cruise passengers used the Port of Barcelona.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The Port Vell area also houses the Maremagnum (a commercial mall), a multiplex cinema, the IMAX Port Vell and one of Europe's largest aquariums – Aquarium Barcelona, containing 8,000 fish and 11 sharks contained in 22 basins filled with 4 million litres of sea water.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] The Maremagnum, being situated within the confines of the port, is the only commercial mall in the city that can open on Sundays and public holidays.
[src:barcelona/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is a major hub for the Spanish rail network.
